          "sections": [
            {
              "label": "The Story",
              "type": "backstory",
              "content": "Jnana Katha, the traditional Lankan rock cookies, can be referred to as Lankan rock cookies or sugar-dipped cookies. It is a traditional, nostalgic tea time biscuit with a rich history, dating back to the Portuguese rule in the 1500s. These have been a staple in the village shops and at homes for generations.\n\nFor me, Jnana Katha brings back memories of huge glass jars in small village shops, with children often sharing them on the way back from school. When I visited my sister back home last year, she had a jar of these made at home and she made some nice cups of tea using tea leaves from a neighboring tea factory. We had some good old yarns over these favorite teatime snacks and warm cups of tea.\n\nToday, I'm happy to make them with Shayan  showing him how to make them all by himself."
            },
            {
              "label": "What You'll Need",
              "type": "ingredients",
              "content": "Ingredients:\n- 100 grams of butter\n- 250 grams of sugar\n- 2 eggs\n- 450 grams of plain flour\n- 2 and a half teaspoons of baking powder\n- Half a teaspoon of baking soda\n- 2 teaspoons of vanilla essence",
              "sub_sections": [
                {
                  "header": "Ingredients",
                  "items": [
                    "100 grams of butter",
                    "250 grams of sugar",
                    "2 eggs",
                    "450 grams of plain flour",
                    "2 and a half teaspoons of baking powder",
                    "Half a teaspoon of baking soda",
                    "2 teaspoons of vanilla essence"
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "label": "How to Make It",
              "type": "preparation",
              "content": "Making the Batter\n\n1. Beat the butter and sugar together, starting with the sugar in the mixer.\n2. Slowly plop in bits of butter into the mixer while it's beating on medium speed.\n3. Add the eggs one at a time; crack them into a separate bowl first to avoid shells.\n4. Sift the flour with the baking powder and soda. \n5. Add the flour into the mixing bowl and beat until all combined.\n5. Using your fingers gather the mixture into a ball.\n6. Then break this into small pieces and form into small balls .\n7. Flatten them on your palm .\n8. Have some sugar in a plate and press one side of the cookie onto the sugar to cover one side completely.\n9. Arrange them on a greased tray and bake for about 20-25 minutes in a 180 degree oven until they begin to turn golden in colour.\n10. Remove from oven and once cool store them in an air tight container for freshness. \n11. Enjoy !!!\n",
