          "qr_image_url": "https://nldppctlsbazaleojhyc.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/brand-assets/qr-codes/recipe-0f8df586-58ea-42af-abd2-48b3ccc1405f.png",
          "sections": [
            {
              "label": "The Story",
              "type": "backstory",
              "content": "Frikadeller is a pan-fried meatball. This is a staple of Danish and Northern German cuisine. It is a vital component of our Lamrais packets. This represents European comfort food with added local spices."
            },
            {
              "label": "What You'll Need",
              "type": "ingredients",
              "content": "- 1 kilo of ground pork, beef, and lamb\n- 2 small brown onions chopped finely\n- ½ cup milk\n- ¾ cup of fresh breadcrumbs\n- 2 large eggs\n- 2 tablespoons of flour\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- ½ teaspoon of all spices\n- Chili flakes to taste",
              "sub_sections": [
                {
                  "header": "Ingredients",
                  "items": [
                    "1 kilo of ground pork, beef, and lamb",
                    "2 small brown onions chopped finely",
                    "½ cup milk",
                    "¾ cup of fresh breadcrumbs",
                    "2 large eggs",
                    "2 tablespoons of flour",
                    "Salt and pepper to taste",
                    "½ teaspoon of all spices",
                    "Chili flakes to taste"
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "label": "How to Make It",
              "type": "preparation",
              "content": "Preparing the Meat Mixture\n\n1. Combine the ground meats with the chopped onions in a large bowl.\n2. Mix the milk and the breadcrumbs separately.\n3. Add the milk-soaked breadcrumbs, egg, flour, salt, pepper, spices, and the chili pieces if you are using to the meat mixture.\n4. Use your fingers to mix this thoroughly until the mixture is sticky.\n5. Cover the bowl and refrigerate for about half an hour.\n\nCooking the Frikadelas\n\n1. Once chilled, take handfuls of the mixture and make small balls and flatten them to about the size of a golf ball.\n2. Heat a generous amount of oil in a pan.\n3. Cook the meatballs on each side for two, four, maybe four to five minutes on a low heat.\n4. Make sure to leave space between the balls and adjust the heat so you do not burn them.\n5. Once cooked, transfer onto a plate with a paper towel underneath to soak up the extra fat.",
              "steps": [
                {
                  "header": "Preparing the Meat Mixture"
                },
                {
                  "text": "Combine the ground meats with the chopped onions in a large bowl."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Mix the milk and the breadcrumbs separately."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Add the milk-soaked breadcrumbs, egg, flour, salt, pepper, spices, and the chili pieces if you are using to the meat mixture."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Use your fingers to mix this thoroughly until the mixture is sticky."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Cover the bowl and refrigerate for about half an hour."
                },
                {
                  "header": "Cooking the Frikadelas"
                },
                {
                  "text": "Once chilled, take handfuls of the mixture and make small balls and flatten them to about the size of a golf ball."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Heat a generous amount of oil in a pan."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Cook the meatballs on each side for two, four, maybe four to five minutes on a low heat."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Make sure to leave space between the balls and adjust the heat so you do not burn them."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Once cooked, transfer onto a plate with a paper towel underneath to soak up the extra fat."
                }
              ]
            },
