          "sections": [
            {
              "label": "The Story",
              "type": "backstory",
              "content": "Kiri Bath, or milk rice, we normally cook this for special occasions like the first of January or the Sinhala New Year, first day of school, or any other special occasion, or any other milestone, or just as a hearty breakfast.\n\nSo this is a traditional dish which can be eaten at any mealtime. It's normally a breakfast, but you can eat it for lunch or dinner."
            },
            {
              "label": "What You'll Need",
              "type": "ingredients",
              "content": "Ingredients:\n- 3 heaped cups of white rice\n- 4 cups of thick coconut milk\n- 5 to 6 cardamom pods crushed\n- Salt to taste\n- Pandan leaf if you have any",
              "sub_sections": [
                {
                  "header": "Ingredients",
                  "items": [
                    "3 heaped cups of white rice",
                    "4 cups of thick coconut milk",
                    "5 to 6 cardamom pods crushed",
                    "Salt to taste",
                    "Pandan leaf if you have any"
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "label": "How to Make It",
              "type": "preparation",
              "content": "Cooking the Rice\n\n1. Wash the rice with cold water.\n2. Add water sufficiently for the rice to cook until soft and turn the rice cooker on, or cook in a pot on a stove.\n\nInfusing with Coconut Milk\n\n1. Once the rice is done and really soft, add the coconut milk with a little bit more salt added to it. It should cover the rice completely.\n2. Turn the rice cooker on again, or if cooking on a stovetop, reduce the heat and let it simmer until it boils and the coconut milk gets soaked into the rice completely.\n3. If doing it on the stove, keep it on the fire until all the rice is soaked in the coconut milk.\n4. If it's in the rice cooker, wait until it is turned off and in the warm setting for about five to ten minutes.\n\nServing\n\n1. Spread the cooked milk rice onto a plate and flatten it.\n2. Let it cool down a little bit.\n3. Cut it into squares or triangles – the traditional way is into triangles.\n4. Serve it in the same dish or arrange it in a different tray, and enjoy it with your favorite accompaniment like a chicken curry, lunu miris, or even pani pol.",
              "steps": [
                {
                  "header": "Cooking the Rice"
                },
                {
                  "text": "Wash the rice with cold water."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Add water sufficiently for the rice to cook until soft and turn the rice cooker on, or cook in a pot on a stove."
                },
                {
                  "header": "Infusing with Coconut Milk"
                },
                {
                  "text": "Once the rice is done and really soft, add the coconut milk with a little bit more salt added to it. It should cover the rice completely."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Turn the rice cooker on again, or if cooking on a stovetop, reduce the heat and let it simmer until it boils and the coconut milk gets soaked into the rice completely."
                },
                {
                  "text": "If doing it on the stove, keep it on the fire until all the rice is soaked in the coconut milk."
                },
                {
                  "text": "If it's in the rice cooker, wait until it is turned off and in the warm setting for about five to ten minutes."
                },
                {
                  "header": "Serving"
                },
                {
                  "text": "Spread the cooked milk rice onto a plate and flatten it."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Let it cool down a little bit."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Cut it into squares or triangles – the traditional way is into triangles."
                },
                {
                  "text": "Serve it in the same dish or arrange it in a different tray, and enjoy it with your favorite accompaniment like a chicken curry, lunu miris, or even pani pol."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "label": "Tips & Variations",
              "type": "tips",
              "content": "Here are some tips and variations for kiri bath:\n\n* Instead of using all white rice, you can use half red rice and half white rice.\n* If you're using kiri bath as a sweetmeat or to decorate a special table, you can add a tiny bit of food coloring to match your other dishes.\n* When serving, try using a large muffin tray. Put a spoonful of kiri bath at the bottom, then add pineapples or luna millies, and top with more kiri bath. Flatten it well with a rolling pin or even some foil with your palm to make it tight. Then, invert it onto a board that fits the muffin tray, and you'll have muffin-shaped kiri bath to serve. This is traditionally called imali kiri bath."
            },
            {
              "label": "Final Thoughts",
              "type": "final_thoughts",
              "content": "Kiri bath is very easy to make and I think all of you will make it into a family staple, rather than keeping it for special occasions. It's nourishing and quite filling as well.\n\nSo you can make it for a weekend breakfast, lunch, or dinner, depending. And also you can pick the accompaniments depending on the time. Make it and enjoy."
            }
          ]
